userStories.notes:
The changes span two files:

1. docs/app/global.css — Add new CSS custom properties and Tailwind theme tokens:
   - In the @theme inline block (around line 4-34), add:
     --color-inline-code-bg: var(--inline-code-bg);
     --color-inline-code-fg: var(--inline-code-fg);
   - In :root (around line 36-56), add:
     --inline-code-bg: #f0ede6;
     --inline-code-fg: #4a3f2f;
   - In .dark (around line 58-77), add:
     --inline-code-bg: #2a2a2a;
     --inline-code-fg: #e0d8c8;
   Note: These are suggested starting colors. The light mode inline-code-bg should be a warm off-white/cream that evokes a retro paper-like feel. The dark mode should be a slightly lighter surface than the page background (#1a1a1a). The foreground colors should have good contrast against their respective backgrounds while being warm-toned to match the retro aesthetic. Feel free to adjust the exact hex values to achieve the right balance.

2. docs/components/MDX.tsx — Update the inline code component (line 82-86):
   Current:
     code: ({ className, children, ...props }: React.HTMLAttributes<HTMLElement>) => (
       <code className={cn('bg-code-bg text-primary relative rounded-(--radius) p-1 text-sm', className)} {...props}>
         {children}
       </code>
     ),
   Change to use the new tokens:
     code: ({ className, children, ...props }: React.HTMLAttributes<HTMLElement>) => (
       <code className={cn('bg-inline-code-bg text-inline-code-fg border border-border/30 relative rounded-(--radius) px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-sm', className)} {...props}>
         {children}
       </code>
     ),

   Important: rehype-pretty-code may inject inline style attributes on code elements that override Tailwind classes. The new styling should work regardless — the background and border are set via Tailwind classes, and the text color from rehype-pretty-code (if present) will still look fine against the lighter background.

   Also important: CodeBlock.tsx renders code blocks inside <pre> elements. The code block <code> elements get their className passed through from rehype-pretty-code (with Shiki theme classes), and the <pre> wrapper in CodeBlock.tsx applies bg-code-bg. The inline code component in MDX.tsx handles bare <code> elements NOT inside <pre>. Since rehype-pretty-code adds data attributes to distinguish inline vs block code, this natural separation should work. But verify that code inside code blocks doesn't accidentally pick up the inline-code styles.
